    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-07-19T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-07-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="827"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d827">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/12552.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Vice Consul <persName type="from">Silliman</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Monterey</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-07-19">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 19, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Governor Carranza received Consul General Hanna, Vice Consul General Robertson
                    and myself this afternoon. The Department’s message of July 16, 7 p.m., was
                    handed him in a formal note. He had previously been fully advised of the
                    contents of the note through a copy furnished Senor Fabela, Acting Secretary for
                    Foreign Relations.</p>
                <p>Governor Carranza appreciates the good offices of the Department of State of the
                    United States and expresses his willingness to meet duly accredited and fully
                    authorized representatives of Acting President Carbajal to agree upon the form
                    of the unconditional delivery of the Government at Mexico City to him as First
                    Chief of the Constitutionalist Army and the unconditional surrender of the
                    forces of the opposition.</p>
                <p>Governor Carranza names Saltillo as the proper and appropriate place to meet the
                    representatives of Acting President Carbajal.</p>
                <p>He suggests that they arrange immediately to attend his representatives there. He
                    also suggests that they come directly north via San Luis Potosí.</p>
                <p>Upon notice of their names and of their departure upon their mission, he will
                    arrange for their personal safety and for the temporary suspension of military
                    operations.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Silliman</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
